data.content:
## EF Core Cosmos DB: Sync-over-async removal in .NET 11

In .NET 10, the Cosmos DB provider let you opt into **sync-over-async** (wrapping async Cosmos SDK calls in blocking `.Result`/`.Wait()`). In .NET 11, **that opt-in is removed entirely**. Every synchronous LINQ operator — `ToList()`, `First()`, `Count()`, and `SaveChanges()` — will throw an `InvalidOperationException` at runtime.

### The fix: convert to async

```csharp
public class ProductRepository
{
    private readonly CosmosDbContext _context;

    public async Task<List<Product>> GetAllAsync()
    {
        return await _context.Products.ToListAsync();
    }

    public async Task<Product> GetByIdAsync(int id)
    {
        return await _context.Products.FirstAsync(p => p.Id == id);
    }

    public async Task<int> GetCountAsync()
    {
        return await _context.Products.CountAsync();
    }

    public async Task SaveAsync(Product product)
    {
        _context.Products.Add(product);
        await _context.SaveChangesAsync();
    }
}
```

### Key points

- **Why it breaks:** The Cosmos DB SDK is natively async-only. Sync-over-async was always a compatibility shim that risked threadpool starvation and deadlocks.
- **What to change:** Every call site up the stack must also become `async`/`await` (controllers, services, etc.).
- **`Add()` is fine** — it's an in-memory operation, not a database call. Only the materializing/executing methods need the async switch.
- Remove any `EnableSyncOverAsync()` or equivalent configuration from your `DbContext` setup — the option no longer exists.
